The psychology of surrender - or why we are willing to pay more
In the case of auctions, the buyers tend to spend more and thus overevaluate the misleading commands.
Neurologists and economic researchers at the University of New York have now succeeded in discovering the neurological-economic foundations of this well-known and seemingly irrational behaviour.
According to a study published in the "Science" magazine, people do not want to beat themselves in a competition, such as a auction on eBay, and are therefore willing to pay even excess prices.
The researchers have tried to explore the neurological scheme of this "game" with experimental auctions.
A group of volunteers should play lotto while the others took part in a playful action - in both cases the active brain regions of volunteers were investigated with functional magnetic resonance (fMRI).
In both games, the participants were able to win money, but an increased activity of the striatum, a complex below the brain belt, was measured in losers of the auction, in which the opponent's surrender played an essential role.
In addition to many other functions, this brain region is responsible for the self-benefit of the nervous system.
The researchers therefore thought that the price increase could be explained by avoiding an overreaction of the striatum.
In order to support their thesis, the economists in the research group have undertaken additional investigations to track the money.
In this case, three groups should offer against a partner under different conditions.
The control group was notified the true value of the product, and then they made their use.
Another group was also promised 15 dollars of reward, in case they were winning from the game.
The third group received 15 dollars before the auction, which were also lost in the case of a lost game.
The difference between the two groups was therefore only that the emphasis on the one was on the profit, while the other was on the loss.
However, as evidence of the hypothesis expressed by neurologians, the members of the "unless losing" group were ready to use higher than those in the control or the "wine" group.
"These results cannot be derived from any previous economic theory.
These have, in fact, found the practices observed in auctions so far only with the pleasure of gaining or avoiding risk.
The contradiction between these two theories was resolved thanks to the imaginative neurologic procedures, so that we now have a third explanation" - said Andrew Schotter, Professor of the Economic Faculty of the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When is the doctor to look for?
Worldwide around half a billion people suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary this chronic liver disease is listed among the leading causes of death.
The number of infected countries is estimated at a hundred thousand, but only seven thousand are treated, which is because patients often do not know that they are infected.
Hepatitis is the term of collection for various viruses of infectious liver diseases.
Symptoms are often similar - liver inflammation and yellowishness are common, but the pathogens and diseases differ.
Hepatitis viruses spread to two different species depending on pathogens: in hepatitis A and E through the digestive tract (e.g. through contaminated food or water), in hepatitis B, C and D, the viruses can be transmitted by blood and other body fluids (e.g. sperm, secrets of divorce or spice).
Travellers are recommended vaccination against the viruses A and B anyway, against the virus C there is no vaccine.
The symptoms of hepatitis A show about two-three weeks after consumption of the contaminated food and are generally accompanied by discomfort, weakness, abdominal pain and breakthrough.
Afterwards the yellow suit appears on the skin and in the eyes, the chair becomes bright, the urine dark, and the recovery can last for up to two-three weeks.
Worldwide, about 1 million people die every year from hepatitis B’s diseases such as liver cancer and liver cirrhosis.
The main reason for this is that estimates suggest that only one tenth infected is in drug mental treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences: untreated can lead to liver cirrhosis and liver cancer.
Most infected people don't even know about their disease, as the pathogen secretly destroys the liver cells - in many cases the first symptoms appear after 20-30 years.
Therefore, timely prevention, such as regular inspections, is essential.
There are three groups in which this disease is more common: those subjected to blood transfusion before 1991, drug addicts and tattooed.
Currently, the number of chronic hepatitis C patients worldwide is estimated at 200 million.
Since the disease is already evidenced in a routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to visit the doctor at the first signs of unknown origin.
Recognizably, the disease is curable, the virus can be eradicated, thus exposing the risk of infection and preventing cancer from emergence.
The 30th September is the World Day of Hepatitis, organised for the first time in 2004 by patient representations worldwide.
The aim of the action is to strengthen consciousness for this chronic liver inflammation caused by viruses, its origin and the significance of early detection.
Do believers have less pain?
As the latest research results show that religious faith acts like a kind of "smudge" that has already facilitated the death of Catholic martyrs.
Scientists at Oxford University have performed an interesting experiment: It was examined how faith in God affects human pain, reported the British sheet "Telegraph".
In the course of the rather bizarre investigation, 12 believers and atheists received electric shocks, while they studied a painting of the mother of God.
As the results showed, believers were able to turn off most of the pains.
By means of a brain scan technology, it could even be demonstrated that the Catholics could activate the part of their brain that is responsible for pain control.
The research was the first in a research project in which, alongside scientists, philosophers and theologians from various departments of the university participated.
During the trial, the volunteers were attached to a sparkling device on the left hand, which gave the electric shocks.
The participants were asked to focus strongly on two paintings: one image of the mother of God, painted by Sassoferrato in the 17th century, and another Leonardo da Vinci's "Dame with the Hermelin".
The researchers hoped that the sight of the Virgin Mary would bring forth a kind of religious trance among the believers, while they chose the image of Vinci, because it was hardly different from other paintings and felt as soothing.
The subjects spent half an hour in a MRI scanner, and at this time they received 20 electric shocks in four stages, while they should either look at the religious, or the other paintings.
The Catholics reported that they had felt "in security" when the mother of God was seen, as if they were "uncared" and they had felt "ruhe and peace".
While considering the religious painting, they reported more than 12% less pain than they had Leonardo’s work in mind.
The psychologist Miguel Farias, who also participated in the attempt, said that similar effects could also be produced with other, strongly working images also with the atheists, one should only find the corresponding photo.
"We would have to find an image that causes very positive feelings, such as a mother or a father," says the psychologist.
The Anglican Bishop Tom Wright welcomed the results of research.
"The practice of faith should change our personality, and in many cases also do it," says Wright.
After these excellent results, only the question remains what effect a Madonna image of Leonardos or another comparable painter would have on the pain regulation of the believers.
Would the high-quality Virgin Mary achieve even better results?
